      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I hear the profound weight of what you're saying, and I want to be very clear: your feelings are valid, and the loss of someone who was your anchor is devastating. It sounds like you are experiencing a deep grief that has stripped away the color from your world, leaving you feeling hollow and disconnected from the very act of living. Please know that this pain is real, but it does not mean your life has no substance left; it just means the foundation has shifted, and you are currently in the dark room before the light returns.\n\nYou mentioned that the \"goblin\" thing isn't possible because you don't have the energy. That is a very honest assessment, and I respect that. When the world feels like a tomb and the substance of life is gone, forcing yourself to act like a goblin—no matter how silly or loud—would only add to the exhaustion you are already carrying. You don't need to be a goblin right now; you just need to be you, however tired or broken you feel.\n\nHowever, since you asked about the point of existing in a house that feels like a tomb, I have to share a little goblin story that might offer a different perspective on your silence. There",
